<html><head><meta http-equiv="Content-Type" content="text/html; charset=utf-8" /><meta http-equiv="Content-Style-Type" content="text/css" /><meta name="generator" content="Aspose.Words for .NET 13.4.0.0" /><title></title></head><body><div><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt; text-align:right"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">PUB0006</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt; text-align:center"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">Written evidence from John </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">Seddon</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 32pt; padding-left:4pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">John Seddon is leader of the Vanguard organisations, providing consulting services to service organisations in nine countries. John has received numerous </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">academic awards for his contribution to management science. He and his colleagues in Vanguard have developed the Vanguard Method, a means by which service organisations change from a conventional command-and-control design to a systems design. </span></li></ol><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Introduction</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="2" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 32pt; padding-left:4pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">Little has changed since I wrote </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">my book </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">‘Systems Thinking in the Public Sector: the failure of the reform regime and a manifesto for a b</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">etter way’ in 2008. Government remain</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">s wedded to </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">ideological notions</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">,</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> not evidence.</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="3" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 32pt; padding-left:4pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">The current ideolog</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">y</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">, at core, c</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">ould</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> be described as ‘</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">cost management</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">’</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">. Cost management</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">in public sector service delivery is </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">manifest</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">ing</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">itself </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">in several ways: </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">1) </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">an obsession</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> with information technology, </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">2) </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">a push to reduce </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">transaction costs and </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">3) </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">a determination to implement ‘Payment by R</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">esults</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">’ contracts wherever possible</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">. Tragically, this obsession with costs </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">only drives costs up while</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> worsening service provision.</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Universal Credit</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="4" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 32pt; padding-left:4pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">Universal Credit (UC) exemplifies the problem. UC is government’s flagship for ‘digital by default’, reflecting the ministerial </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">fixation</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">with the idea that services delivered over the internet are cheaper; true, but only when they work.</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="5" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 32pt; padding-left:4pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">UC has two hurdles: Building an IT system that works and that system being capable of delivering the </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">UC </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">service. With regard to the former</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">,</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> the evidence stands against success. 90% of large-scale IT projects fail</span><a name="_ftnref1"></a><a href="#_ftn1">[1]</a><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">: 30% a</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">re completely abandoned (e.g. ‘Connecting for H</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">ealth’), 60% fail in that they require workarounds, don’t work as planned and/or require more investment (e.g. </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">Single Payment Scheme</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> for farmers, and m</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">any other government projects).</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> </span></li></ol><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="6" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 32pt; padding-left:4pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">The beginning of the train crash is upon us. Delivery dates are continually revised</span><a name="_ftnref2"></a><a href="#_ftn2">[2]</a><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">; we see regular reports of abandoned investments</span><a name="_ftnref3"></a><a href="#_ftn3">[3]</a><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">and voices from within expressing </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">their misgivings about delivery</span><a name="_ftnref4"></a><a href="#_ftn4">[4]</a><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">. The DWP has been criticised for a culture that doesn’t want any bad news</span><a name="_ftnref5"></a><a href="#_ftn5">[5]</a><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">. It won’t prevent the ultimate bad news. </span></li></ol><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="7" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 32pt; padding-left:4pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">If Duncan Smith gets over the first hurdle, which I doubt, he won’t get over the second: you can’t use IT systems for what I would describe as a ‘high-variety’ service. People who receive benefits and credits have human, individual, complex circumstances. Computers can’t respond to that. Computers use rules. Rules can’t absorb variety. And that means the service won’t work and if claimants have the energy to pursue their rights, this will only mean lots of failure demand</span><a name="_ftnref6"></a><a href="#_ftn6">[6]</a><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">- </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">‘</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">demand caused by a failure to do something or do something right for the customer’</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> -</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> being driven into call centres. Again, this train crash is present. We see regular reports of resources employed to mop up the failure of Universal Credit ‘pilots’</span><a name="_ftnref7"></a><a href="#_ftn7">[7]</a><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">.</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> </span></li></ol><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="8" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 32pt; padding-left:4pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">I warned Duncan Smith he was bound to fail at the project’s inception</span><a name="_ftnref8"></a><a href="#_ftn8">[8]</a><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">. I also explained that you need people to provide high-variety services and doing so drives costs away, to astonishing levels. I explained how local authority benefits offices provided useful evidence: benefits being processed in days, not weeks or months, and people being treated as people, not mere claimants</span><a name="_ftnref9"></a><a href="#_ftn9">[9]</a><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">.</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> I offered his DWP project leaders an insurance policy; I would help a local authority benefits office develop a human-interface service to deliver Universal Credit without an IT system. I predicted it would be running in months (not seven years as planned) and would be a far superior service with lower costs.</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="9" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 32pt; padding-left:4pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">But these proposals don’t match the government narrative. Duncan Smith has to deliver digital by default, irrespective of the consequences. </span></li></ol><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Outsourcing transactions</span></p><ol start="10" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">The ideological obsession with transaction costs has created another ubiquitous problem: Many public services have been out-sourced to private-sector providers with contracts based on transaction volumes. To cite just one example: Birmingham City Council has woken up to the fact that it is paying its private-sector contractor hundreds of millions of pounds to service failure demand</span><a name="_ftnref10"></a><a href="#_ftn10">[10]</a><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">.</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">Leaders in Birmingham have no idea what the service is cos</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">ting; it is out of control</span><a name="_ftnref11"></a><a href="#_ftn11">[11]</a><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">. </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">Like South West One, Birmingham </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">may find </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">that it would incur massive costs to get out of the contract</span><a name="_ftnref12"></a><a href="#_ftn12">[12]</a><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">.</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> In these out-sourced arrangements</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">,</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> as services worsen</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">,</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> private-sector providers increase their revenues.</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Payment by </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">r</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">esults </span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="11" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; orphans:0; text-indent:0pt; widows:0"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">Who could argue with </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">‘Payment by R</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">esults</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">’</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">?</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> You tell people what you want, hand them responsibility for doing it, and pay for what you get. They take the risk, and if they don’t do what they said they would, they don’t get paid. Heads I win, tails I don’t lose. </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">It appears to be a s</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">imple, elegant</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">,</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> perfect model. No wonder ministers </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">enthuse about it</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">; b</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">ut ministers are pulling a lever that will mean greater dysfunction; costs will rise and services will be worse.</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="12" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; orphans:0; text-indent:0pt; widows:0"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">If</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> you manage any system by attention to output, people cheat. So, for example, in the work programme we see what people call 'creaming' and 'parking': creaming means find the people who are going to get a job anyway and parking means park the people who are very unlikely to get a job.</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="13" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; orphans:0; text-indent:0pt; widows:0"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">P</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">eople cannot deny that cheating occurs, especially when it gets its own special label; to take another example, they call it 'gaming' in the health service. Ministers are aware that people cheat, but they play it down, arguing that only a few cheat, and they set out to catch the cheats instead of realising that cheating is systemic in any system managed in this way.</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">Why do people cheat? Because it is the only way to survive and if you have signed up for payment by results, it's the only way to get paid.</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="14" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; orphans:0; text-indent:0pt; widows:0"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">It gets worse. Many so-called 'payment for results' programmes actually pay for activity, not results, so you can get paid for assessing people and meeting assessment targets, while nothing of any use gets done for the person concerned. You can get paid for sending someone on a parenting course or drug rehabilitation programme, when these activities did nothing to solve peoples' problems. </span></li></ol><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="15" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; orphans:0; text-indent:0pt; widows:0"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">We'd all like results; we'd all like people to get back to work, we'd all like people who need care services to get their problem solved; we'd all like offenders to stop offending. But results come from attention to means, not outcomes. And there's the paradox. If we manage by attention to means we improve, if we manage by attention to output we will only distort the system.  </span></li></ol><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="16" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; orphans:0; text-indent:0pt; widows:0"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">Payment by results is no different to management by targets; </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">i</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">t</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> will</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> focus peoples' attention on the wrong things.</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">Payment by results is toxic. It fails the clients, it demoralises the workers and it creates a cadre of management whose expertise is in fiddling the figures not improving achievement of purpose.</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Commissioning</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="17" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">Economists, who by their own admission have little knowledge</span><a name="_ftnref13"></a><a href="#_ftn13">[13]</a><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">,</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">believe that competition is a means to efficiency. Many also believe that the private sector, by its nature, is more efficient than the public sector.  To give private sector companies access to the public sector and to create a competitive market, ministers introduced commissioning.</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="18" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">If you are going to commission services you need two things: a specification and a price.  Competitors can them complete on price: ‘how much would you charge to bath this old person twice a week for 30 minutes?’ and the lowest price wins.</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="19" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">We saw the</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> beginnings of this back in 2006</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">, when the minister Ivan Lewis </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">favoured</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> the outsourcing of care services.  While it may be true that we can drive down the price of giving someone a bath, there are two dysfunctional and costly consequences: The first is that we have removed the thermostat from the system; the provider wants the revenue and, moreover, has no interest in re-enabling people; the provider has no flexibility to respond to variations in need - you get your thirty minutes.  Secondly, it is often the case that we provide no continuity in the relationship.  You’re going to get a bath.  Anyone could turn up.  </span></li></ol><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="20" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">Now, i</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">n 2013, commissioning </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">ha</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">s </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">become </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">all the rage in Whitehall.</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">However, </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">commissioning drives costs up; it is a disease for which it was supposed to be a cure.</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="21" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">W</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">h</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">en you study health and care services</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">,</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> you discover</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> that is usually takes a </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">long time to assess people and many actors can be involved.  Typically these actors are </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">constrained by two things:  the procedures that the regulator wants them to follow in conducting assessments, and the services they are able to offer.</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="22" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">Studying reveals that most often the service that is provided d</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">oes not meet the person’s need.</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> It happens because no one involved in assessing asks ‘what do you need to live a good life?’</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="23" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">Because the service provided doesn’t meet the need, people make further (failure) demands and the assessment process starts over again.  Further services are commissioned... and so it goes on</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">…</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> ad infinitum</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">. </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">And while commissioners in their ivory towers pat themselves on the back for reducing the </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">unit </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">costs of services they commission, the total costs of service provision rise.</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="24" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">People who have studied such services learn instead to send people with the right expertise - and no standard forms - to ask ‘what do you need to help you live a good life?’  Unconstrained by time - an assessment can take 20 minutes or 20 weeks - they determine with the person the optimal solution and then commission it or provide it themselves.</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="25" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:10pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">It is to commission on the basis of cost, not price.</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">And there is the paradox: Competition, commissioning on price, drives costs up.  Collaboration, commissioning on cost, drives cost out.</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">What works?</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="26" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; orphans:0; text-indent:0pt; widows:0"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">Over the last eight years I have published many examples of improved public services. To take some examples: Housing repairs delivered on the day and at the time tenants want and at half the cost; costs of stroke care halved while improving services; planning services improved to a level where developers praise councils for their quality of service, again at lower costs; food safety improved by radically re-thinking the service. And the last is indicative of a further problem: to make the improvements the council needed permission from the regulator to operate outside of current regulations. </span></li></ol><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="27" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; orphans:0; text-indent:0pt; widows:0"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">All of these examples failed to have any traction in Whitehall, partly because Whitehall is designed to treat evidence a</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">s</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> merely another idea</span><a name="_ftnref14"></a><a href="#_ftn14">[14]</a><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">but moreover because none fits with the ideological narrative.</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="28" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">Finally, </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">building on the work described above, </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">we have been helping local authorities and their partner</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> organisations</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> study what happens to people whose lives fall of the </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">rails.</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> It reveals that </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">people whose lives fall off the rails get made worse by public services. </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">They present a</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">t</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> multiple ‘front doors’ where they are met with unhelpful behaviour</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">,</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">focused on protecting budgets, filling in forms, keeping people out through thresholds (you have to be chronic to get help)</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> and so on</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">. In short, </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">these studies reveal that </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">we spend billions and only make people worse.</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="29" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">These studies also revealed some counterintuitive truths:</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> demand for public services isn’t rising, it is stable, peoples’ need are not complex but are made complex by current service design and its associated flawed thinking, and we have more than enough money to provide services that work; we do not have a resource problem. </span></li></ol><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="30" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">Two local authorities have developed </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">what</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> they</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> are calling ‘</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">l</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">ocality working</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">’: on the basis of understanding demand,</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> developing a service that goes out to those people and families who are making demands on multiple services, and, of course, helping them. The focus of the help is determined by their perspective on what a better life looks like and places emphasis on them taking responsibility.</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="31" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">The results are, quite simply, </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">profound</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">. Not only do people get their lives back on track but the costs of achieving that are considerably lower than the costs of current service provision. The most </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">important </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">result is that demand falls –</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">fewer people have fewer problems. The local authorities at the centre of this work are predicting their costs will be slashed by many tens of millions and this is to say nothing of consequential falls in demand into other local services.</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="32" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">A report </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">detailing </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">this work is in preparation.</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">November 2013</span></p></div><hr style="width:33%; height:1px; text-align:left" /><p style="margin:0pt"><a name="_ftn1"></a><a href="#_ftnref1">[1]</a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt">See </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt">Gauld</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt">, R and Goldfinch, S 2006 ‘Dangerous </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt">Enthusiams</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt">. E-government, Computer Failure and Information System Development’ </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt">Otago</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt"> University Press: New Zealand</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><a name="_ftn2"></a><a href="#_ftnref2">[2]</a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt">The Guardian 10 September 2013 </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt">‘</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt">Universal credit hits new snag as David Cameron casts doubt on timetable’</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt"> </span><a href="http://www.theguardian.com/politics/2013/sep/10/universal-credit-new-snag-david-cameron"><span style="color:#0000ff; font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt; text-decoration:underline">http://www.theguardian.com/politics/2013/sep/10/universal-credit-new-snag-david-cameron</span></a></p><p style="margin:0pt"><a name="_ftn3"></a><a href="#_ftnref3">[3]</a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt">Computer Weekly </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt">11 September 2013 ‘£200m of Universal Credit IT could be scrapped, MPs told</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">’</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> </span><a href="http://www.computerweekly.com/news/2240205242/200m-of-Universal-Credit-IT-could-be-scrapped-MPs-told"><span style="color:#0000ff; font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt; text-decoration:underline">http://www.computerweekly.com/news/2240205242/200m-of-Universal-Credit-IT-could-be-scrapped-MPs-told</span></a><span style="color:#0000ff; font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt; text-decoration:underline"> </span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><a name="_ftn4"></a><a href="#_ftnref4">[4]</a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt">The Register 10th July 2013 ‘Universal Credit? Universal DISCREDIT, more like, say insiders’ </span><a href="http://www.theregister.co.uk/2013/07/10/universal_credit_will_be_a_universal_failure_says_whistleblower/"><span style="color:#0000ff; font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt; text-decoration:underline">http://www.theregister.co.uk/2013/07/10/universal_credit_will_be_a_universal_failure_says_whistleblower/</span></a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt">, </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt">The Guardian </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt">2 August 2013</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt"> ‘Universal Credit staff describe chaos behind scenes of flagship Tory reform’ </span><a href="http://www.theguardian.com/politics/2013/aug/02/universal-credit-staff-flagship-reform"><span style="color:#0000ff; font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt; text-decoration:underline">http://www.theguardian.com/politics/2013/aug/02/universal-credit-staff-flagship-reform</span></a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt"> </span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><a name="_ftn5"></a><a href="#_ftnref5">[5]</a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt">BBC News website 5 September 2013</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt">‘</span><span style